{"title_page": "Irish road bowling", "text_new": "{{short description|Sport played with metal balls in some parts of Ireland}}\n{{Infobox sport\n| name       = Irish road bowling\n| image      =Road Bowling.jpg\n| alt        = \n| imagesize  = \n| caption    = \n| union      = \n| nickname   = \n| first      = \n| firstlabel = \n| region     = Ireland\n| registered = \n| clubs      = \n| contact    = \n| team       = \n| mgender    = \n| type       = \n| equipment  =  [[round shot|cannonball]] of c.{{convert|18|cm|in|0}} circumference and {{convert|28|oz|g|0}} weight\n| venue      = a road\n| olympic    = no\n| world      = no\n| paralympic = no\n| obsolete   = \n}} Arriba espana\n'''Road bowling''' ({{lang-ga|B\u00f3l an bh\u00f3thair}}; also called ['''long''']''' bullets''')<ref name=\"lane2005\">{{cite book |title=Long Bullets: A History of Road Bowling in Ireland |first=Fintan |last=Lane |location=Cork |publisher=Galley Head Press |year=2005 |isbn=095421594X}}</ref> is an Irish  sport in which competitors attempt to take the fewest throws to propel a metal ball along a predetermined course of country roads.<ref name=\"aaiintro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/|title=General Introduction|work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> The sport originated in [[Ireland]] and is mainly played in counties [[County Armagh|Armagh]] and [[County Cork|Cork]].\n\nSpectators often bet on the outcome and proffer advice to their favoured competitor in the course of a match or \"score\".  Road bowling in Ireland is governed by the voluntary Irish Road Bowling Association ({{lang-ga|B\u00f3l Chumann na h\u00c9ireann}}). The 2016 All-Ireland Series took place in [[Madden, County Armagh]].<ref name=\"MercyHosp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/other-sports/classy-killian-kingston-pulls-off-double-366913.html |date=25 November 2015 |accessdate=26 November 2015 |archivedate=26 November 2015 |url-status=live |title= Classy Killian Kingston pulls off double |first=Seamus |last=\u00d3 Tuama |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126145816/http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/other-sports/classy-killian-kingston-pulls-off-double-366913.html}}</ref>\n\n== Rules and playing style ==\nThe \"bullet\" or \"bowl\" ({{lang-ga|b\u00f3l}}) is an solid iron [[round shot|cannonball]] of c.{{convert|18|cm|in|0}} circumference and {{convert|28|oz|g|0}} weight.<ref name=\"aaiintro\"/><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishroadbowling.ie/about.htm | publisher = Irish Road Bowling Association | website = irishroadbowling.ie | title = Bol Chumann na hEireann - About Us | accessdate = 26 April 2017}}</ref>   There are two or more players or teams in a match or \"score\".<ref name=\"aaiintro\"/> The one with the fewest shots to the finish line wins. If two players or teams approach the finish line with equal shots, the winner is decided by which throw goes farther past the finish line.<ref>{{cite news|title=In This Kind of Bowling, the Lanes Have Cars|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324634304578537950707359438?mod=ITP_AHED|newspaper=WSJournal}}</ref>\n\nA ''road shower'' advises the thrower about the throw (or shot) much like a [[golf caddy]], while another helper stands ahead of the thrower, feet apart, to show the best line or path in the road.\n\nThe thrower runs to the throwing mark and, in the Northern or [[County Armagh]] style, extends the arm and bowl behind him as he runs. At the throwing mark the arm is snapped forward by arching the back and shoulders, releasing the bowl underhand before stepping over the mark.\n\nIn the Southern or [[County Cork]] style, as the thrower runs to the mark the arm and bowl are lifted up and back, then whirled downward into an underhand throw, releasing the bowl before stepping over the mark.\n\nWherever the bowl stops (not where it leaves the road surface), a [[chalk]] mark is made at the nearest point on the road and the next throw is taken from behind that mark.\n\nOver tight curves, or corners where two roads meet, the bowl may be thrown through the air (lofted). The loft must strike the road or pass over it. If the loft fails to reach the road, it counts as one shot, and the next throw must be taken again from the same mark.\n\n==History==\nFintan Lane, in his book ''Long Bullets: A History of Road Bowling in Ireland'', traces the sport to the 17th century and suggests that it was once far more widespread than it is today.<ref name=\"lane2005\"/> Until the 19th century, the game was also played in Scotland, the north of England and in North America.<ref name=\"lane2005\"/>  In the past, players were given twenty shots (a score) each, the winner determined by who went the greatest distance. Though the modern game is a fixed distance in fewest shots, the expression \"score\" for a match survives.  Disputes between competitors or spectators often created public disturbance and courtcases resulted down to the 1950s.<ref name=\"aaihist\"/>\n\nBol-Chumann na h\u00c9ireann was formed in 1954 to replace the less organised All-Ireland Bowl Players Association.<ref name=\"aaihist\"/> There were irregular contests between Cork and Armagh champions over the decades,<ref name=\"aaihist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/early-history/|title=Early History |work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> but the first national championship between them was in 1963.<ref name=\"aaibol\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/early-history/bol-chumann-na-heireannth/|title=B\u00f3l Chumann na h\u00c9ireann/The National Assoc.|work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The first World Championship was as part of [[Cork 800]] in 1985.<ref name=\"aaiintl\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nThe Irish form of road bowling is concentrated in counties Cork and Armagh (especially south Armagh).<ref name=\"lane2005\"/> It is also played in [[County Mayo|Mayo]] ([[Castlebar]]), [[County Limerick|Limerick]], [[County Waterford|Waterford]], [[County Louth|Louth]], [[County Monaghan|Monaghan]] and more recently in [[County Tyrone|Tyrone]] and [[County Wexford|Wexford]] and also in Dagenham, London, UK.<ref name=\"aaiintro\"/>\n\n[[Klootschieten]] is a similar game played in the [[Netherlands]] and northwest [[Germany]] ([[Friesland]] and [[Schleswig-Holstein]]) and international events have been staged between these regions and Ireland.<ref name=\"aaiintl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/early-history/international/|title=International|work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Irish game also has players in [[Boston, Massachusetts]];<ref>[http://www.wbur.org/2010/04/13/road-bowling WBUR report] on road bowling in the Boston area</ref> [[Cambridge, New York]], and [[Bennington, Vermont]], vicinity;<ref>[http://slirb.org/ State Line Irish Road Bowling, Cambridge, New York, & Bennington, Vermont] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705153632/http://slirb.org/ |date=2012-07-05 }}</ref> Middletown, Connecticut;{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} [[Traverse City, Michigan]];<ref>[http://sites.google.com/site/bansheebowling/ Northern Michigan Banshees Road Bowling Club]</ref> [[the Bronx, New York]]; [[New Zealand]]; [[Asheville, North Carolina]];<ref>[http://www.ashevilleroadbowling.com/ Asheville Irish Road Bowling Association, Asheville, North Carolina] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312055721/http://www.ashevilleroadbowling.com/ |date=2010-03-12 }}</ref> Savannah, Georgia <ref>http://www.aohsavannah.com/#!__road-bowling-home</ref> and is growing in the fairs and festivals of the state of [[West Virginia]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A11321-2005Mar29.html Washington Post - Go Play in the Road]</ref> The largest Irish road bowling event in the world is held annually in September in Wheeling, West Virginia, with 737 bowlers participating in 2016.{{fact|date=September 2016}}\n\nThe first contest in [[Colborne, Northumberland County, Ontario|Colborne, Canada]] was held on May 26, 2007. An annual tournament during the weekend of or prior to [[Saint Patrick's Day]] takes place in [[Portland, Oregon]].{{fact|date=August 2019}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song ''Out the Road'' by [[Gaelic Storm]] is about a road bowling score. Additionally, footage of a road bowling score is included in a YouTube video shot by band founders Pat Murphy and Steve Twigger about their trip to Murphy's native County Cork during the production of their album ''[[Chicken Boxer]]'' (which includes ''Out the Road'').\n\n=== Terminology ===\nGame terminology (as used primarily in Ireland) includes:   \n;bowl of odds: when one bowler is one full shot fewer than his opponent, i.e., when a bowler is equal to or farther in distance than his opponent, but has thrown one less shot.\n;break butt:  To step over the ''butt'' before releasing the bowl\n;bullet: the bowl that is thrown or \"shot\"\n;bullets: County Armagh name for the game of road bowling. Also ''long bullets''. See also ''bullet''.\n;butt: the throwing mark on the road. See also ''break butt''\n;corner: a sharp curve in the road or a corner where two roads meet. See also ''open the corner''\n;f\u00e1g a' bealach!: anglicised as [[Faugh A Ballagh]] and meaning \"clear the way\" (to warn spectators on the road in front of the thrower)\n;get sight: see ''open the corner''\n;kitter-paw:a left-handed thrower (from {{lang-ga|cite\u00f3g}}<ref name=\"McArthurMcArthur2005\">{{cite book|last1=McArthur|first1=Thomas Burns|last2=McArthur|first2=Roshan|title=Concise Oxford Companion to the English Language|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QMsWFsI0YkIC&pg=PT717|accessdate=9 July 2012|date=2005-12-15|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780192806376|page=717|chapter=Hiberno-English}}</ref>)\n;loft:to throw through the air.\n;long bullets: see ''bullets''\n;open the corner: also ''get sight''. to throw so deeply into the curve that the next throw is a straight shot out.\n;score: a match\n;shot: a throw\n;sop:a tuft of grass placed in the road at a spot where the bowl should first strike the surface. An experienced bowler can \"split the sop\". (from {{lang-ga|sop}}, meaning a \"small bundle (of straw)\")\n;stylish bowler:a bowler with a smooth well-coordinated delivery.\n\n==Notable bowlers==\n* [[Mick Barry (bowler)|Mick Barry]] (1919\u20132014) of [[County Cork]] was All-Ireland Champion on eight separate occasions between 1965 and 1975.<ref name=\"aaibarry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/mick-barry/|title=Mick Barry 'The Bowlplayer of all time' |work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/king-of-the-road-dies-95-301478.html | publisher= Irish Examiner | date= 8 December 2014| title= \u2018King of the road\u2019 dies, 95 }}</ref>\n* [[John Buckley (bishop)|John Buckley]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cork and Ross|Roman Catholic bishop of Cork and Ross]], sometimes bowled in his cassock. \n* Stephen Wallington of [[Cabell County, West Virginia]], is the current Novice 1 North American Road Bowling Champion.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.herald-dispatch.com/features_entertainment/local-road-bowler-headed-to-competition-in-ireland/article_193eb1ad-a0b3-51c6-aa50-ddff7c483b3c.html| publisher= Herald Dispatch, Huntington, WV | title= Local road bowler headed to competition in Ireland | date= 19 August 2014}}</ref>\n* Joe McVeigh (1925\u20131990) of Armagh won several All-Ireland titles in the 1950s, and broke the record for the noted Knappaph course just outside Armagh, completing it in 22 shots. The record still stands, and a commemorative headstone is placed at the roadside to acknowledge the achievement.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n*Martin Coppinger of Bantry, County Cork was several times an All-Ireland senior champion.{{fact|date=September 2017}}\n*David Murphy of Innishannon, County Cork was European champion on three separate occasions and All-Ireland senior champion.{{fact|date=September 2017}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Klootschieten]] - a similar sport played in the far eastern parts of the Netherlands, and in northern Germany.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishroadbowling.ie/ Irish Road Bowling Association] Official website\n* [http://www.wvirishroadbowling.com/ West Virginia Irish Road Bowling Association] Official website\n\n{{Bowling}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irish Road Bowling}}\n[[Category:Irish road bowling| ]]\n[[Category:Bowling]]\n[[Category:Bowling in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Sports originating in Ireland|Road bowling]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sport played with metal balls in some parts of Ireland}}\n{{Infobox sport\n| name       = Irish road bowling\n| image      =Road Bowling.jpg\n| alt        = \n| imagesize  = \n| caption    = \n| union      = \n| nickname   = \n| first      = \n| firstlabel = \n| region     = Ireland\n| registered = \n| clubs      = \n| contact    = \n| team       = \n| mgender    = \n| type       = \n| equipment  =  [[round shot|cannonball]] of c.{{convert|18|cm|in|0}} circumference and {{convert|28|oz|g|0}} weight\n| venue      = a road\n| olympic    = no\n| world      = no\n| paralympic = no\n| obsolete   = \n}}\n'''Road bowling''' ({{lang-ga|B\u00f3l an bh\u00f3thair}}; also called ['''long''']''' bullets''')<ref name=\"lane2005\">{{cite book |title=Long Bullets: A History of Road Bowling in Ireland |first=Fintan |last=Lane |location=Cork |publisher=Galley Head Press |year=2005 |isbn=095421594X}}</ref> is an Irish  sport in which competitors attempt to take the fewest throws to propel a metal ball along a predetermined course of country roads.<ref name=\"aaiintro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/|title=General Introduction|work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> The sport originated in [[Ireland]] and is mainly played in counties [[County Armagh|Armagh]] and [[County Cork|Cork]].\n\nSpectators often bet on the outcome and proffer advice to their favoured competitor in the course of a match or \"score\".  Road bowling in Ireland is governed by the voluntary Irish Road Bowling Association ({{lang-ga|B\u00f3l Chumann na h\u00c9ireann}}). The 2016 All-Ireland Series took place in [[Madden, County Armagh]].<ref name=\"MercyHosp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/other-sports/classy-killian-kingston-pulls-off-double-366913.html |date=25 November 2015 |accessdate=26 November 2015 |archivedate=26 November 2015 |url-status=live |title= Classy Killian Kingston pulls off double |first=Seamus |last=\u00d3 Tuama |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126145816/http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/other-sports/classy-killian-kingston-pulls-off-double-366913.html}}</ref>\n\n== Rules and playing style ==\nThe \"bullet\" or \"bowl\" ({{lang-ga|b\u00f3l}}) is an solid iron [[round shot|cannonball]] of c.{{convert|18|cm|in|0}} circumference and {{convert|28|oz|g|0}} weight.<ref name=\"aaiintro\"/><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishroadbowling.ie/about.htm | publisher = Irish Road Bowling Association | website = irishroadbowling.ie | title = Bol Chumann na hEireann - About Us | accessdate = 26 April 2017}}</ref>   There are two or more players or teams in a match or \"score\".<ref name=\"aaiintro\"/> The one with the fewest shots to the finish line wins. If two players or teams approach the finish line with equal shots, the winner is decided by which throw goes farther past the finish line.<ref>{{cite news|title=In This Kind of Bowling, the Lanes Have Cars|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324634304578537950707359438?mod=ITP_AHED|newspaper=WSJournal}}</ref>\n\nA ''road shower'' advises the thrower about the throw (or shot) much like a [[golf caddy]], while another helper stands ahead of the thrower, feet apart, to show the best line or path in the road.\n\nThe thrower runs to the throwing mark and, in the Northern or [[County Armagh]] style, extends the arm and bowl behind him as he runs. At the throwing mark the arm is snapped forward by arching the back and shoulders, releasing the bowl underhand before stepping over the mark.\n\nIn the Southern or [[County Cork]] style, as the thrower runs to the mark the arm and bowl are lifted up and back, then whirled downward into an underhand throw, releasing the bowl before stepping over the mark.\n\nWherever the bowl stops (not where it leaves the road surface), a [[chalk]] mark is made at the nearest point on the road and the next throw is taken from behind that mark.\n\nOver tight curves, or corners where two roads meet, the bowl may be thrown through the air (lofted). The loft must strike the road or pass over it. If the loft fails to reach the road, it counts as one shot, and the next throw must be taken again from the same mark.\n\n==History==\nFintan Lane, in his book ''Long Bullets: A History of Road Bowling in Ireland'', traces the sport to the 17th century and suggests that it was once far more widespread than it is today.<ref name=\"lane2005\"/> Until the 19th century, the game was also played in Scotland, the north of England and in North America.<ref name=\"lane2005\"/>  In the past, players were given twenty shots (a score) each, the winner determined by who went the greatest distance. Though the modern game is a fixed distance in fewest shots, the expression \"score\" for a match survives.  Disputes between competitors or spectators often created public disturbance and courtcases resulted down to the 1950s.<ref name=\"aaihist\"/>\n\nBol-Chumann na h\u00c9ireann was formed in 1954 to replace the less organised All-Ireland Bowl Players Association.<ref name=\"aaihist\"/> There were irregular contests between Cork and Armagh champions over the decades,<ref name=\"aaihist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/early-history/|title=Early History |work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> but the first national championship between them was in 1963.<ref name=\"aaibol\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/early-history/bol-chumann-na-heireannth/|title=B\u00f3l Chumann na h\u00c9ireann/The National Assoc.|work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The first World Championship was as part of [[Cork 800]] in 1985.<ref name=\"aaiintl\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nThe Irish form of road bowling is concentrated in counties Cork and Armagh (especially south Armagh).<ref name=\"lane2005\"/> It is also played in [[County Mayo|Mayo]] ([[Castlebar]]), [[County Limerick|Limerick]], [[County Waterford|Waterford]], [[County Louth|Louth]], [[County Monaghan|Monaghan]] and more recently in [[County Tyrone|Tyrone]] and [[County Wexford|Wexford]] and also in Dagenham, London, UK.<ref name=\"aaiintro\"/>\n\n[[Klootschieten]] is a similar game played in the [[Netherlands]] and northwest [[Germany]] ([[Friesland]] and [[Schleswig-Holstein]]) and international events have been staged between these regions and Ireland.<ref name=\"aaiintl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/early-history/international/|title=International|work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Irish game also has players in [[Boston, Massachusetts]];<ref>[http://www.wbur.org/2010/04/13/road-bowling WBUR report] on road bowling in the Boston area</ref> [[Cambridge, New York]], and [[Bennington, Vermont]], vicinity;<ref>[http://slirb.org/ State Line Irish Road Bowling, Cambridge, New York, & Bennington, Vermont] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705153632/http://slirb.org/ |date=2012-07-05 }}</ref> Middletown, Connecticut;{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} [[Traverse City, Michigan]];<ref>[http://sites.google.com/site/bansheebowling/ Northern Michigan Banshees Road Bowling Club]</ref> [[the Bronx, New York]]; [[New Zealand]]; [[Asheville, North Carolina]];<ref>[http://www.ashevilleroadbowling.com/ Asheville Irish Road Bowling Association, Asheville, North Carolina] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312055721/http://www.ashevilleroadbowling.com/ |date=2010-03-12 }}</ref> Savannah, Georgia <ref>http://www.aohsavannah.com/#!__road-bowling-home</ref> and is growing in the fairs and festivals of the state of [[West Virginia]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A11321-2005Mar29.html Washington Post - Go Play in the Road]</ref> The largest Irish road bowling event in the world is held annually in September in Wheeling, West Virginia, with 737 bowlers participating in 2016.{{fact|date=September 2016}}\n\nThe first contest in [[Colborne, Northumberland County, Ontario|Colborne, Canada]] was held on May 26, 2007. An annual tournament during the weekend of or prior to [[Saint Patrick's Day]] takes place in [[Portland, Oregon]].{{fact|date=August 2019}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song ''Out the Road'' by [[Gaelic Storm]] is about a road bowling score. Additionally, footage of a road bowling score is included in a YouTube video shot by band founders Pat Murphy and Steve Twigger about their trip to Murphy's native County Cork during the production of their album ''[[Chicken Boxer]]'' (which includes ''Out the Road'').\n\n=== Terminology ===\nGame terminology (as used primarily in Ireland) includes:   \n;bowl of odds: when one bowler is one full shot fewer than his opponent, i.e., when a bowler is equal to or farther in distance than his opponent, but has thrown one less shot.\n;break butt:  To step over the ''butt'' before releasing the bowl\n;bullet: the bowl that is thrown or \"shot\"\n;bullets: County Armagh name for the game of road bowling. Also ''long bullets''. See also ''bullet''.\n;butt: the throwing mark on the road. See also ''break butt''\n;corner: a sharp curve in the road or a corner where two roads meet. See also ''open the corner''\n;f\u00e1g a' bealach!: anglicised as [[Faugh A Ballagh]] and meaning \"clear the way\" (to warn spectators on the road in front of the thrower)\n;get sight: see ''open the corner''\n;kitter-paw:a left-handed thrower (from {{lang-ga|cite\u00f3g}}<ref name=\"McArthurMcArthur2005\">{{cite book|last1=McArthur|first1=Thomas Burns|last2=McArthur|first2=Roshan|title=Concise Oxford Companion to the English Language|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QMsWFsI0YkIC&pg=PT717|accessdate=9 July 2012|date=2005-12-15|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780192806376|page=717|chapter=Hiberno-English}}</ref>)\n;loft:to throw through the air.\n;long bullets: see ''bullets''\n;open the corner: also ''get sight''. to throw so deeply into the curve that the next throw is a straight shot out.\n;score: a match\n;shot: a throw\n;sop:a tuft of grass placed in the road at a spot where the bowl should first strike the surface. An experienced bowler can \"split the sop\". (from {{lang-ga|sop}}, meaning a \"small bundle (of straw)\")\n;stylish bowler:a bowler with a smooth well-coordinated delivery.\n\n==Notable bowlers==\n* [[Mick Barry (bowler)|Mick Barry]] (1919\u20132014) of [[County Cork]] was All-Ireland Champion on eight separate occasions between 1965 and 1975.<ref name=\"aaibarry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/sports-recreation/sport/road-bowling/mick-barry/|title=Mick Barry 'The Bowlplayer of all time' |work=Road Bowling|publisher=Ask About Ireland|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/king-of-the-road-dies-95-301478.html | publisher= Irish Examiner | date= 8 December 2014| title= \u2018King of the road\u2019 dies, 95 }}</ref>\n* [[John Buckley (bishop)|John Buckley]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cork and Ross|Roman Catholic bishop of Cork and Ross]], sometimes bowled in his cassock. \n* Stephen Wallington of [[Cabell County, West Virginia]], is the current Novice 1 North American Road Bowling Champion.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.herald-dispatch.com/features_entertainment/local-road-bowler-headed-to-competition-in-ireland/article_193eb1ad-a0b3-51c6-aa50-ddff7c483b3c.html| publisher= Herald Dispatch, Huntington, WV | title= Local road bowler headed to competition in Ireland | date= 19 August 2014}}</ref>\n* Joe McVeigh (1925\u20131990) of Armagh won several All-Ireland titles in the 1950s, and broke the record for the noted Knappaph course just outside Armagh, completing it in 22 shots. The record still stands, and a commemorative headstone is placed at the roadside to acknowledge the achievement.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n*Martin Coppinger of Bantry, County Cork was several times an All-Ireland senior champion.{{fact|date=September 2017}}\n*David Murphy of Innishannon, County Cork was European champion on three separate occasions and All-Ireland senior champion.{{fact|date=September 2017}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Klootschieten]] - a similar sport played in the far eastern parts of the Netherlands, and in northern Germany.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishroadbowling.ie